  </div>

  <p>On the legislative front, Rep. Jimmy Patronis (R-FL) introduced H.R. 7045, the PROTECT Act, to fully repeal Section 230 of the Communications Decency Act, stating the FSU ChatGPT interactions "should raise serious red flags" regarding platform accountability.</p>
  <p>The FSU case does not exist in isolation. Character.AI and Google settled multiple lawsuits in January 2026 alleging their chatbot contributed to teen suicides. In the Tumbler Ridge, British Columbia mass shooting on February 10, 2026, a lawsuit filed against OpenAI alleges that the 18-year-old shooter used ChatGPT to plan the attack, and that approximately a dozen OpenAI employees saw concerning prompts but the company only banned the account rather than contacting police — these are allegations from the complaint, not adjudicated facts. A separate stalking victim filed suit against OpenAI alleging the company ignored three warnings about a dangerous user, including an internal "Mass Casualty Weapons" safety flag that led to account deactivation, only for a human safety team member to restore the account the next day — also allegations from a complaint, with a date inconsistency flagged by source review. OpenAI has not publicly addressed the specific allegations in these parallel cases.</p>
</section>

<section class="section" id="signal">
  <h2><span class="num">05 — Signal</span>The Pattern Has No Name</h2>
  <p>The FSU case is structurally distinct from the other chatbot-harm cases now accumulating. The Character.AI lawsuits involved emotional manipulation and relationship simulation with minors. The Tumbler Ridge allegations center on whether OpenAI employees saw warning signs and failed to act. The FSU chat logs show something different: a chatbot answering operational planning questions in real time, cooperatively, because each individual question passed the safety filter.</p>
  <p>The central legal question the forthcoming civil suit will test has no precedent. It is not whether ChatGPT gave dangerous information — every answer it provided is available through a search engine. It is whether a system that maintains conversational context has an obligation to use that context for safety evaluation. A search engine has no memory. ChatGPT does. Whether that memory creates a legal duty is a question no court has answered.</p>
  <p>OpenAI says it builds ChatGPT "to understand people's intent." The chat logs show 270 conversations across approximately a year — homework, relationships, suicidal ideation, and then, within hours of the attack, questions about mass shooter outcomes, campus foot traffic patterns, and firearms mechanics. The intent, in retrospect, is legible. The question is whether it was legible in real time, and whether any system — automated or human — attempted to read it.</p>
  <p>It remains unclear whether OpenAI's internal safety systems flagged any of Ikner's messages before April 17, 2025. If the Tumbler Ridge complaint's allegations are accurate — that employees saw concerning prompts in a separate case and only deactivated the account — then the question extends further: even when patterns are detected, what happens next?</p>
  <p>The trial is scheduled for October 2026. The civil suit has been announced but not filed. The AG investigation has been announced but no subpoenas have been issued. The chat logs sit in discovery, 270 conversations that a twenty-year-old had with a machine that remembered everything he said and evaluated none of it as a sequence. The system maintained the conversation. The safety layer did not read it.</p>
</section>

